12. Vertical Slicing

[00:00:00]

What is going on crafters? Khalil here. And in this video, we are going to talk about vertical slicing, which is the first of the physical essentials. And we're going to cover all of the physical and theoretical essentials at a pretty high level right now,so that when we move into the phases of craftship and we begin to use these, we could build on a baseline understanding of these mental models.

So what is vertical slicing? It's a way for us to decompose the work that we need to do into manageable chunks. If you think back to this idea of what design is, this, idea of discoverability and understanding.

We have to make sure that when we're writing code, it is very easy for us to find the things that we need to find. If you can't see your features from the folder structure alone, there's a good chance maintainability is under pressure. And this is a very common thing.

Oftentimes when we're working from a code [00:01:00] first perspective, we tend to organize our files and features in our project folder structure just based on the type of infrastructure it is.

We've talked about this already before, this is packaging by infrastructure. It's something that hurts maintainability, it hurts design, it hurts discoverability and understanding.

There's two other things that often happen here too, where we might just be thinking about the work that we're doing in terms of just adding more code And this might not seem like a big deal, but it really is a big deal because it is the internal representations that we have in our minds, the mental models that we're working off of.

That's what is going to show up in our code, and that's what is going to be understood by other developers as they look at our code as well. This thinking where we're just adding code in, this is called a transaction script approach to thinking, and it's almost as if all we're doing is working against just a bunch of tiny little scripts in our code, and it's not all that effective in terms of maintainability.

Or [00:02:00] perhaps maybe you're starting your work from React components. Now, that's not the worst thing to do, however, because it is not quite closely aligned towards what the key developer use case is, which is to primarily work against features, not to work against components.

It will have this adverse... Effect on the maintainability of our code. I'm saying here the key developer use cases are to discover, understand, add, change, remove, test and debug features. So because of this, you want to chunk your work, your modules, your features and your operations. There's a difference between these two into vertical slices of functionality.

What is the difference between a feature and an operation? A feature is something that is valuable to the customer. For example, we might have a user story where a person registers and signs up for, let's say, a premium package on some sort of membership website.

That is a user story that is going to involve many API calls. It's taking someone through [00:03:00] an experience from A to B. And. During the process of going through that feature, we're going to have to execute a number of operations. Those operations are going to change the system, like create user, and they're going to be ones that get information from the system, get user or get profile details.

Ultimately features are the thing that is most valuable for the customer. It's the thing that they want. It's the thing that has business value, and we want to make sure that these become first class citizens in terms of how we structure our code base and how we move into doing our work.

So that is a very important thing to say, and we will learn how to do this.

Now, operations, they are more of the low level slices. I said these are things that will change the system or get information from the system.

That makes them commands or queries. These are effectively your API calls. It is these things that come together in sequence to build up a feature itself. [00:04:00] So if we want to think about the most valuable thing we can test, It's not actually going to be the operations themselves, like createUser or editUser or things like that.

The most valuable thing we can test is actually going to be the features themselves.

So ultimately, this physical essential works and it's effective because we're working against the reality of what we're dealing with here. The reality is we work against features. Features come from the customer and the customer needs.

And those features have user stories, which explains a way that someone is going to move through the system and experience it.

And if this is the primary thing that we're going to be working against as developers, it would only make sense for us to make it very easy for other developers to jump into our code base and be able to discover features, understand them, change them, remove, test them, debug them.

That's what we're trying to do with vertical slicing.

So maybe take a moment to reflect on how you're currently doing things and ask yourself,[00:05:00] can you see the features in your codebase? If someone else needed to look into your codebase, would they be able to identify where the features are?

How easy or how hard would that be?

And when we get to think back to the pillars of what makes code scalable, that's the architecture, design, testing, and strategy.

You can see that vertical slicing is related to a number of different topics. Each of which we are going to cover in more detail throughout the phases of craftship. It's good to know this at a high level, how this fits into the grid or the matrix of topics that matter.

And once we get the features from the theoretical guess points, we move into the physical ones, and it's from here that we get to write our acceptance tests, and later on I'll teach you about how to use high value units, and high value integration tests as well, to test your features.

Purely, or to test your features in a different way, where you don't have to go through the front end of the system. You can actually test more of the internals of your system, [00:06:00] be it on the front end or the back end. This ability to isolate out different bits and pieces of how you're testing your features, sometimes this is necessary depending on the context you're dealing with.

For example, if you are a front end developer and

The backend isn't quite yet ready, but you want to be able to test your features and make sure that they're going to work properly. You're going to need a way to do that. You're going to need a way to isolate out the stuff that's not quite there and mock or simulate the behavior of the backend that is yet to come.

So this is a very high level of vertical slicing. We're going to get into this in a lot of detail and attack this from many angles throughout the phases of craftship.

In particular, in best practice first, is when we're going to spend a lot of time on vertical slicing. It's probably one of the more straightforward essentials to apply and understand.

We're also going to return to it in pattern first as well. When we get to talk about separating code paths into read and write paths and [00:07:00] read models and write models and things like that, that will help us create a one directional event driven architecture.

And there are lots of great reasons for that, but I won't get into them just now, so let's continue along to the next essential.
